Of course you'd need some populist shill like Johansson playing the objective and disillusioned "lawful good" character. Almost as if she wouldn't sacrifice her principles for comedic purposes, why her acting is so stiff and dreadful, and why she's an emotionless personality vacuum. Can't wait to yawn whenever she's on screen. 
Don't want to be the guy to bring historical accuracy into a satirical comedy, but nazification was so severe, that a kid wouldn't dare question if it was a good time to be a Nazi or not; because it always was. Or at least, that's what the ministry of propaganda was feeding them. If you want people to understand the actual seriousness of the tone you're setting underneath all that comedy and for the political climate Germans lived in at the time; because I'd assume sending that message was your intention given the circumstances; you need to believe that your main character is also subjected to that propaganda. The mothers character would be willingly sending her son off to Hitler youth, putting up pictures of Nazi propaganda all over the house, and painting Hitler as the ideal husband in her own head. Infact, it's a wonder she would be single at all in Nazi Germany without a man keeping her secure. As sexist as it sounds, and I assume feminism and strong independent women is their intention, she should be on the street or desperately trying to find a husband. Not making her own way in the upper echelons of Nazi society. Giving a woman so much power without earning it actually downplays the sacrifices they made to get there, and only hides the real challenges women faced not just in Germany, but other places around the world too. With something for the character to face and accept or challenge, it becomes their redemption story; rather than a one dimensional "I'm a good guy now" plot. Or maybe I'm looking too much into it and it really is just a movie for kids, which sends very mixed messages.

I'm attracted to this marvelously quirky movie.  In an odd, far-reaching way (and from a deep, psychological perspective), it harkens Dr Jordan Peterson's warnings/admonitions about man's capacity for malevolence (and from that, how to fortify yourself to possibly resist it).  Specifically, Peterson talks about how any one of us - including himself - would have most likely "fallen-in with the crowd" of being a Nazi or BrownShirt in Germany circa 1930s.  It's easy to try and see ourselves as a social and spiritual hero of the day - say, an Anne Frank, or Dietrich Bonhoeffer, or Oskar Schindler - but only the rarest of us would have such stout, brave constitution.  Most of us would have succumbed to the omnipotent psychological phenomenon and brainwashing.  Taika Waititi tackles this deep, personal struggle in his own quirky, humorous style through the eyes of the young protagonist, Jojo.  It's fascinating, really.  (And just for the record, I, too, fear that I would have fallen in with the crowd back then.  Groupthink can be a very powerful setting; it's a mental state that can only be truly and honestly assessed after-the-fact.)

Finally, a movie that dares to mock Nazis. I wonder how a movie like this got made in Hollywood, and I applaud the filmmakers for their bravery in challenging conventions and delivering an urgent message that has not yet been heard.

Oh, sorry, I was thinking of _The Great Dictator._ Since Nazism ceased to be politically relevant about 75 years ago, this movie either doesn't have a political message or it's a stupid and immoral message conflating modern-day non-violent conservatives and nationalists with National Socialist fanatic mass murderers. _The Great Dictator_ was a tremendous moral stand, _The Producers_ was a brave successful approach of a taboo subject, this is just satirizing the easiest possible target, one that is historical and no longer extant in any meaningful, influential sense.

Don't get me wrong, I enjoy making fun of Nazis and pointing out their tremendous evil, but with the current political climate I'm expecting this movie will at least be promoted as relevant to contemporary politics, which is to say it will portray center-right politicians like Donald Trump and Boris Johnson as somehow modern-day Nazis. Obviously not relevant since they're not starting wars, mass murdering millions of people, launching genocidal campaigns, are not totalitarians or authoritarians, are opposed to socialism, and are in charge of liberal democracies with fair and free elections and rule of law.

That said, with politics aside, I like Taika Waititi and the cinematography is very pretty to look at (nice and colorful with no obvious horrible color grading), so I'll probably enjoy this film as I did _Hunt for the Wilderpeople._ I don't mind Waikiki casting himself in whiteface as Adolf Hitler. He'll almost certainly be good in the role. Looks like fun. If I was a comedian, I'd relish playing a Nazi in a movie like this.
